Boxing Statistics

1 Aims and objectives

1.1 Introduction

in this report, I will be looking at male boxers and the correlation between their wins, losses, number of total fights. I will attempt to find the correlation between Orthodox and Southpaw fighters and their win rates.

I chose this project because I am genuinely curious to see the results and how natural language processing and complex web scraping are encorporated. </p>

descriptions


Orthodox
A fighter who fights with left hand and foot in front (generally a right handed person)
Southpaw
A fighter who fights with right hand and foot in front (generally a left handed person)

This is of great interest to me as I am left handed myself, so I am interested to learn if being in this minority group has some benefits.

Background

There is a myth that a Southpaw fighter has an advantage over Orthodox fighters because their fighting stance is more uncommon and rarely seen during training, thus resulting in more a complex fight. Most people agree that this is just a myth; however, it is still told frequently within martial arts communities.

I plan to evaluate the folowing questions:

  • If 10% of the general population is lefthanded, does that make 10% of boxers Southpaw?
  • How do their wins and losses compare to those of Orthodox boxers?
  • Do Southpaws win with more knockouts because their opponents are unable to anticipate their moves?

I will not be taking into account who is fighting who; for example, whether the fight is between Orthodox vs Southpaw, Orthodox vs Orthodox, or Southpaw vs Southpaw. I anticipate that this may leave gaps in the data, which I will try to mitigate.

1.2 Aims and objectives

The objectives of this project are as follows:

  1. To gather a dataset that can be worked on
  2. To sanitise and save the dataset to be easily and safely worked on
  3. To prove or disprove the theory Southpaw boxers have an advantage other Orthodox fighters
  4. To demonstrate that this data is being used ethically
  5. To clearly display the results in this report, utilising various techniques

The aims of this project is to answer the following questions:

  • Is the ratio of Orthodox to Southpaw boxers the same as the ratio of lefthanded to right handed people in general?
  • Do Southpaw boxers have an advantage over Orthodox fighters?
  • Which group of fighters are more likely to win by knockout?
  • Which group of fighters have a better win:loss ratio?

1.3 The data

I chose to use Wikipedia to collect data because their website has all text available under the Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike License, which makes it easier to retrieve the data and also safer from a legal perspective.

As Wikipedia has webpages of pure lists, I have found a list of male boxers with each name on the list linking to their individual biographical articles. By utilising the page of lists first, I plan to then extract the desired data from each individeual page.

Wikipedia was also chosen because their website is well structured with pages often following a pattern. For example, a page about a person often has the same information box on the right hand side, which includes their name, a picture, and some basic pieces of data. It is this area of the page that I am specifically interested in.

import re

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

1. Creating the data structure

The data structure is set up initially with only the boxers name and the link required to go to their biographical article.

I have chosen to use data frames from pandas as they are easy to manipulate. Later in the process I plan to use the built in ability of pandas to access table data from webpages, which should prove useful as most biographical articles have the same table displaying very similar (if not the same) information.

In [304]:
page = urllib.request.urlopen("https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_male_boxers")
soup = bs(page, 'html.parser')

# initialise the lists that will be fed into the data frame
links = []
names = []

allLinks = soup.find(id="bodyContent").find_all("a")
linkToScrape = 0

for link in allLinks:
    if link['href'].find("/wiki/") == -1: 
        continue

    # Use this link to scrape
    linkToScrape = link
    links.append(linkToScrape['href'])
    names.append(linkToScrape['title'])

    
df = pd.DataFrame({'name' : names, 'link': links})

2. Removing unwanted rows

As you can see below, this data frame contains some rows that are not intended to be used going forward. As there are only a few and as they are ony at the end or beginning of the data, I removed them by hand so to speak.

4. Testing the links

This for loop adds the biographical article to the end of Wikipedias standard URL, then prints them to the screen. This allows me to confirm that the links are correct and will work for the next step.

5. The function

Below is the function that does much of the heavy lifting. The boxerScrape function uses the links found earlier to visit each biographic article for each person on the list and finds the appropriate data from the info table.

The function ends immediately if the webpage is not responding and gives an appropriate error message.

We initialise the variables that are used to populate the dictionary object. This way, if a piece of data is missing, a 0 or an empty string is then given instead of the program failing or giving NaN.

In the for loop, if a specific heading exists, then the variable is updated to hold the information next to the correct heading. Here we also print what we have found, so we can see that it is working correctly while the function is working. By doing this, we do not need to wait for the function to finish to know if there were any problems. I have not seen a big performance difference, so i chose to keep them for ease of use of the program.

Finally, the dictionary object is returned.

In [312]:
def boxerScrape(link):
    
    response = requests.get(url=link)
#   check that the webpage is available
    if response.status_code != 200:
        return "something went wrong: " + link
#   initialise the variables that will be put into the dictionary object
    nationality = ''
    stance = ''
    total = 0
    wins = 0
    ko = 0
    losses = 0
    draws = 0
#   printing the link here helps if there is an error, 
#   errors often happen after this step so knowing the page the error came from is very helpful
    print(link)
#   try and except block, prevents the program from failing if there is an erorr, 
#   instead prints a message to the console
    try:
#       scrape all the table elements using pandas
        scraper = pd.read_html(link)
#       put the first table into our temporary dataframe
        data = pd.DataFrame(scraper[0])
#       loop over the dataframe to pick out the information that we are looking for
        for row in data.index:
            if data.iloc[row][0] == 'Nationality':
                print ('Nationality = ' + data.iloc[row][1])
                nationality = data.iloc[row][1]
            if data.iloc[row][0] == 'Stance':
                print ('stance = ' + data.iloc[row][1])
                stance = data.iloc[row][1]
            if data.iloc[row][0] == 'Total fights':
                print ('total = ' + data.iloc[row][1])
                total = data.iloc[row][1]
            if data.iloc[row][0] == 'Wins':
                print ('wins = ' + data.iloc[row][1])
                wins = data.iloc[row][1]
            if data.iloc[row][0] == 'Wins by KO':
                print ('KO = ' + data.iloc[row][1])
                ko = data.iloc[row][1]
            if data.iloc[row][0] == 'Losses':
                print ('losses = ' + data.iloc[row][1])
                losses = data.iloc[row][1]
            if data.iloc[row][0] == 'Draws':
                print ('draws = ' + data.iloc[row][1])
                draws = data.iloc[row][1]
#       populate the dictionary with the information we were able to scrape.
        dict = {'Nationality': nationality,
                'Stance' : stance, 
                'Total fights': total, 
                'Wins': wins, 
                'KO': ko, 
                'Losses': losses, 
                'Draws': draws}
    except:
        print("an error occured")
        return
#   return the dictionary
    return dict

6. Calling the function

A new data frame is created to take the dictionary returned from the function.

We loop over all the links using the same for loop that was tested in step 4, but this time calling the function that I described earlier.

Another temporary data frame is used to recieve the dictionary, then it is concatenated with the output dataframe to form our main set of data which will be used later.

In [313]:
output = pd.DataFrame()
# loop over all the links we found
for link in df['link']:
#   call the function and put the returned information directly into a variable
    data = boxerScrape("https://en.wikipedia.org" + link)
    
    print(data)
#   populate the output dataframe
    df_dictionary = pd.DataFrame([data])
    output = pd.concat([output, df_dictionary], ignore_index=True)
    print(output.head())

8. Bringing them together

Both of our dataframes (output and df) have the same number of rows, which means the function worked correctly. If a link was missing, it would not populate the output dataframe and would return fewer that 749 rows.

Once merged, we can finally begin analysing this data.

In [322]:
df_output = pd.concat([df, output], axis = 1)

10.2 NaN entries

Removing the NaN entries from the data frame, and replacing them with a string "-"

This should prevent errors when parsing the data

In [520]:
boxersData['Nationality'] = boxersData['Nationality'].fillna('-')
boxersData['Stance'] = boxersData['Stance'].fillna('-')

10.4 Correcting missing data, continued

The script below loops over the data frame and adds wins, losses, and draws together if the total fights = 0 but one of the other headings mentioned != 0, Total fights will be recalculated

In [524]:
for index, row in boxersData.iterrows():
    if (row['Total fights'] == 0):
        if (row['Wins'] != 0 or row['Losses'] != 0 or row['Draws'] != 0):
            row['Total fights'] = (row['Wins'] + row['Losses'] + row['Draws'])
            print(row['Total fights'])

10.5 Checking it worked

As we can see, the list produced is now empty, meaning that there are no more 'Total fights' entries that are 0 erroneously.

11. Calculating the percentage of Southpaw fighters

Here I will attempt to find the percentage of fighters that are Southpaw, and compare that to the global average of lefthanded people.

In [636]:
orth = 0
south = 0
none = 0

for index, row in boxersData.iterrows():
    if (row['Stance'][0] == 'O' ):
        orth = orth +1
    if (row['Stance'][0] == 'S'):
        south = south +1
    if (row['Stance'] == '-'):
        none = none +1
    

stance_dict = {'Orthodox': orth, 'Southpaw': south, 'No data': none}
stance_dict
percent = south / (south+orth) *100
percent = str(percent)
print(stance_dict)
print("the percentage of southpaw fighters is: " + percent)

{'Orthodox': 373, 'Southpaw': 83, 'No data': 284}
the percentage of southpaw fighters is: 18.201754385964914

11.1 Visualising the result

Above we can see the percentage of Southpaw fighters is 18.2% according to the data available.

This is interesting because the percentage of the general public being left handed is around 10% on average.

According to a study of 2.3 million people published in the Psychological Bulletin (Papadatou-Pastou et al., 2020), a meta-analysis of 262 datasets found left handedness ranged from 9.3% to 18.1%. I find it difficult, but not impossible, to believe that the number of Southpaw professional fighters is a coincidence.

The bar graph below shows the number of Orthodox compared to the number of Southpaw fighters. There are also many entries with no data under this heading, but can be reviewed later to see if it makes a difference.

In [617]:
stance = list(stance_dict.keys())
values = list(stance_dict.values())

        width = 0.5)

12. Calculating the difference in performance

As set out in my aims and objectives, I seek to discover if there really is an advantage to being left handed as a professional boxer. I shall take the average of both sets of boxers for each heading.

In [688]:
ms = pd.DataFrame(boxersData[boxersData['Stance'] == 'Southpaw'].mean())
mo = pd.DataFrame(boxersData[boxersData['Stance'] == 'Orthodox'].mean())
ms = ms.rename(columns={0:'Southpaw'})
mo = mo.rename(columns={0:'Orthodox'})
extract = ms['Southpaw']
mm = mo.join(extract)
In [689]:

Both sets of boxers above have similar trends to their wins, losses, draws, and total fights, which I found interesting. 13. KOs

Southpaw fighters gain an additional edge as shown by the graph above. Although the difference is only 2%, it may be neglegable. On average, Southpaw fighters win by knockout 57.5% of the time, while Orthodox fighters win 55.5% of the time.

Although there is no evidence to show that Southpaw fighters are stronger or more powerful than Orthodox fighters, the myth we are testing is that it is more difficult for an Orthodox fighter to fight a Southpaw fighter because they are so rarely fought against. The data shows that the myth may be true with Southpaw fighters winning and getting knockouts slightly more often. This suggests that Southpaw fighters may be able to exploit gaps in their opponents training and experience, alowing then to score more points or get a knockout punch.

On the other hand, as KOs are a subset of wins, it stands to reason that KO rate will correlate with win rate.

14. Proportions

While looking at the graph above, I noticed that the 'total fights' bars had the greatest difference which I believe requires further investigation.

In [743]:
# get the difference between their totals by calculating Southpaw - Orthodox
# a possitive number will show that the difference is in favour of Southpaw
# a negative number will show that the difference is in favour of Orthodox
mm['S-O, Diff'] = mm['Southpaw'] - mm['Orthodox']
# a value > 0 shows that Orthodox has a greater value than Southpaw, and vice versa
mm['proportion'] = mm['Orthodox'] / mm['Southpaw']
mm

Orthodox Southpaw S-O, Diff proportion

Losses 10.449864 5.675000 -4.774864 1.841386
Total fights 64.430894 44.700000 -19.730894 1.441407
Wins 51.252033 37.950000 -13.302033 1.350515
Win % 79.545741 84.899329 5.353588 0.936942
KO % 55.520305 57.575758 2.055453 0.964300

14.1 Proportions

At first glance, when looking at the difference between Southpaw and Orthodox fighters, it appears that Orthodox fighters had many more total fights on average than Southpaw fighters. At first I believed this could be evidence that Southpaw fighters may have shorter careers, or this could be the beginning of a conspiracy theory that Southpaw fighters are unfairly given fewer fights. To test this, I checked to see if these differences were proportional.

The proportions tell a different story, I expected the proportion for total fights to be the highest, but it is actually one of the lowest. The figure most out of proportion is draws, but these numbers are already so low that this might be an error enduced by the small sample size. On the other hand, it shows that Losses is the second most disproportionate statistic. Southpaw fighters have almost half as many losses compared to Orthodox fighters. This further confirms my suspitions that Southpaw fighters have an advantage.

15.1 Final observation

'std' for 'total fights' is far lower for Southpaw than for Orthodox fighters. This may be because of the range we see in the dataset with Southpaw having a range of 147 total fights and Orthodox having a range of 358. The information brings into question the reliability of this data and my findings. This is a limited dataset because Wikipedia doesn't have a list of ALL male boxers - just those famous or notable enough for someone to create an article about them.

I move to conclude.

16. Conclusion

Through this exploratory analysis of male boxers, I can conclude that there seems to be a slight competitive advantage to being Southpaw in terms of their percentage of wins to losses.

I conclude that the myth I stated in the beginning of this report is plausible at the least as there is now some evidence that shows Southpaw fighters win 5% more often, on average, than their Orthodox counterpart.

I conclude that the data analysed was reliable enough for the sake of answering this question, but more research is required to give a definitive answer to this question.
